skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "41011e3c-70d5-4f1c-9e09-364ce979811c", "value": "The movement of earth/soil, not necessarily leading to the alteration of landforms and/or the burial of archaeological sites."}

skos:Concept.skos:definition: {"id": "6a6949b1-b809-4977-8d4e-168c429f0753", "value": "Specialisation of \"Slopes\", where the slope is (near to) 90 degrees."}

{"id": "2e18b9b4-8007-45ba-b9d0-aa4cfa90409c", "value": "A natural act involving an overflow from a water body, beyond its normal limits. This can lead to archaeological features being covered or submerged under a body of water. This term is differentiated from inundation"}

{"id": "a5f8f9b4-7fbc-4eb3-9fd7-48abb1c64093", "value": "This term covers a series of effects (e.g. erosion/weathering) which are caused by the flow and movement of bodies of water (i.e. sea, lake, river, 'wadi') and/or by the flow and movement of the wind, but where it is uncertain which of the two or both were responsible."}

{"id": "b41abb6b-8859-470d-a267-ca929a0d053e", "value": "The act of clearing and/or flattening/destroying ground or archaeological features/modern buildings etc., where it is not clear whether this has been carried out using mechanised machinery or by hand."}
{"id": "931d5e3c-3350-4233-bfb8-2a59dd0042e6", "value": "An explosive charge laid on or just under a surface (anthropogenic or natural)"}
{"id": "884cb6da-dcc6-4c96-b6e6-a6abb526c6ed", "value": "The artificial and deliberate provision of water by the means of pipes, sprinklers, drains, ditches etc."}
{"id": "0bad2437-c966-424e-9b18-62cc7f91e8fb", "value": "The presence of anthropogenically planted and/or managed orchards, forests and/or woods (silviculture)."}

{"id": "b509997b-b6c9-40d0-9dc1-cff3b6a6f310", "value": "The extraction of natural resources/geological materials i.e. metals, stone etc. from the earth by scraping or working the surface of the ground, often with machinery such as bulldozers. Most often in alluvial contexts."}
{"id": "f79de3de-e1d0-4100-bf8b-3da122d337e7", "value": "The act of clearing and/or flattening/destroying ground or archaeological features/modern buildings etc., by hand/using handtools."}

{"id": "3fb79922-10f7-4cf8-a038-455ea249a638", "value": "This term should be used to indicate that, given the current evidence, there is no evidence for damage and/or threat to the archaeological site mentioned in published imagery or identifiable from imagery sources."}
{"id": "83ed3f0b-8be1-4531-94e0-588166b7485f", "value": "The release of energy in an often sudden and violent way. This can lead to the sudden shattering or blowing apart of objects/features."}
{"id": "c75aff97-7f71-4fea-a352-be3613c81bc6", "value": "A track or network of tracks along which a train runs. Usually composed of a series of steel rails running along the ground."}

{"id": "8641fb8d-f96d-49b7-b427-572e0b65e69b", "value": "The delibreate act of changing the contours of the land/earth's surface. This can include landscaping in order to produce terraces, as well as the deposition of imported soil, raising the level of land surface/"}

{"id": "bd77ad7e-f70a-48df-a4aa-4608f748c5a9", "value": "Lack of upkeep activities, and legal frameworks (e.g legal enforcement of protection of heritage places) to look after sites. This category also includes lack of tourism and management strategies (such as the lack of human and financial resources and conservation plan, etc.) on a heritage site."}

{"id": "e1612225-11d6-4830-b0ed-28b1423c9386", "value": "The extraction of natural resources/geological materials i.e. metals, stone etc. from the earth by excavating under the surface of the ground, accessed through tunnels, shafts, or caves."}

{"id": "d0df7a8e-0faf-47f3-a3c9-3cff6ca63d89", "value": "Shifts in the environmental conditions at a site/of a feature. This definition would include changes in moisture content at both a local and regional level, as well as shifts in the comparative scales of hot and cold."}

{"id": "e155ca23-5ca1-4daa-a95e-9cbabb0541ad", "value": "The act of writing or drawing (can be scratched, painted etc.) something onto a surface. In this case the surface of an archaeological object, feature or site."}
{"id": "f7dfad1d-18fb-406a-b430-f37a89dfaf3d", "value": "The violent discharge of steam/volcanic material from an active vent in the earth's crust"}

{"id": "f56517db-db53-4e73-917b-589abd5281fb", "value": "The act of making a hole using a boring or rotating mechanism. Drilling can be associated with activities such as Oil extraction and the sinking of well systems."}

{"id": "b4ef5892-0ad1-4da4-b632-923765d6e882", "value": "An anthropogenic act involving an area being covered/overwhelmed with water. This is differentiated from flooding by being defined as a deliberate and anthropogenic act."}

{"id": "a22e3898-fd9e-489e-af2e-7cf788efac47", "value": "This term covers a series of effects (e.g. erosion/weathering) which are caused by the flow and movement of the wind. It does not include temperature and humidity changes which are listed as a separate cause."}

{"id": "65f165f7-9782-4fe8-aa62-38ffb233125c", "value": "The contamination of the land, water, air etc., by the presence or introduction of poisioness or harmful substances. This can cover pollution arising from natural disasters, as well as pollution caused by dense urbanization etc."}

{"id": "daefb706-21a6-4c42-8f84-b298cb511e26", "value": "The act of creating/digging a usually narrow passage or channel through earth/rock. This process can be connected with mining activities and the construction of hydrological features."}
{"id": "ed15a43a-028a-4967-9902-ae8415080272", "value": "The act of digging trenches across a landscape and the provision of water through that system to an area."}

{"id": "675b9d04-7b3d-4906-8a2e-10bd014ef1a8", "value": "The act of trying to prevent or limit the loss of archaeological material using scientific methods. This does not cover actions or processes that attempt to maintain access to or create walkways etc. as a way of maintaining archaeological sites for tourism etc. "}
{"id": "c41deeee-992d-499c-a59d-7e6e19cc66a7", "value": "The act of removing material (e.g. stone/mudbrick) from an archaeological site. "}

{"id": "9388c3d7-8d37-4090-b10d-b22f217c6fa4", "value": "This term covers a series of effects (e.g. erosion/weathering) which are caused by the flow and movement of bodies of water (i.e. sea, lake, river, 'wadi'). It does not include flooding and precipitation which are listed as separate causes."}

{"id": "b142c810-21d9-40eb-a215-ecdb6e21a920", "value": "The act of digging or creating a hole/trench by hand/hand tools for a purpose other than mining/quarrying. This term can be used to cover archaeological excavation or excavation for the purposes of looting."}
{"id": "9347d952-efe4-486d-861c-592dbbb73641", "value": "Cultivated or natural plant cover"}

{"id": "19e9e217-6fb7-4d9f-bad1-641513fc937e", "value": "The extraction of natural resources/geological materials i.e. metals, stone etc. from the earth by excavating pits or trenches into the surface."}
{"id": "a5e75919-66cb-483e-9b23-cb5bbf692728", "value": "The act of firing or letting off small scale weaponry e.g. guns as opposed to the use of artillery."}
{"id": "22eb3490-bb8c-44ec-a327-fed1aa77962b", "value": "The extraction of natural resources/geological materials i.e. metals, stone etc. from the earth, by unknown means"}

{"id": "db4d6c83-f52c-4b62-8c73-e3c3e2e40b73", "value": "The returning of a place to a known earlier state by removing accretions or by reassembling existing elements without the introduction of new material."}

{"id": "ac275862-591f-46ff-b30d-b2a02646e4c6", "value": "Presence of non-moving objects used in transport e.g. cars, tanks etc., at a site. For example, the presence of stationary tanks may indicate that the site is under military control."}
{"id": "a4eb8687-fc32-43eb-ae36-097e88e81749", "value": "The act of deliberate breaking and damage of heritage."}

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "93ebaf24-0674-4d76-95b3-ba394f18b39f", "value": "Invasion/inhabitation by living organisms in numbers or quantities large enough to be harmful. This includes burrowing."}

skos:Concept.skos:definition: {"id": "1b681bc6-52e8-4a31-847f-bdc41e9205c8", "value": "Removal of non-structural items (for structural use structural robbing) e.g immovable objects, site panels or signage. record when signage is stolen from a site or items from a museum. Note: use \"Excavation\" linked to \"Looting\" when looter's holes are seen but you do not definitely know that material has been removed from the site."}

{"id": "5beab882-6356-47af-bb65-f1b96f7140bd", "value": "The condensation of water vapour in the earth's atmosphere which leads to water falling in the form of rain, snow, sleet etc. and being deposited on the earth's surface."}
{"id": "52a9dae9-8c6e-4a9d-b7e8-953bf41a1723", "value": "The collapse/movement of a mass of earth or rock, generally down a slope."}

{"id": "6c2f1579-9a7d-4310-b1dd-3046dbba82cd", "value": "The act of destruction or tearing down of archaeological structures. This act can be carried out both in a controlled and uncontrolled manner, but also using both mechanised and/or hand machinery"}
{"id": "63f47204-5fbe-4805-b381-780adaada64d", "value": "The action of disposing of unwanted material, including scrap material and waste."}

{"id": "7f567a1b-de9d-4fb5-b432-c9b774cf059a", "value": "The act of digging or creating a hole/trench for a purpose other than mining/quarrying where it is not clear whether this has been carried out using mechanised machinery or by hand. This term can be used to cover archaeological excavation or excavation for the purposes of looting."}
{"id": "65ad5fd8-680c-4c21-9523-5da37edef947", "value": "The act of animals consuming vegetation/and or being moved across an area of land whether that vegetation be natural or planted."}

{"id": "fa5045f8-55b6-4c44-ad28-60ee2d76bad2", "value": "The act of trying to keep archaeological sites in good condition, possibly through the addition of modern features, such as walkways etc. on a heritage site. It includes the implementation of upkeep and maintenance activities to look after sites. This category also includes both implementation of tourism and management strategies (such as the addition of modern features e.g. walkways, dedication of human resources and development of conservation plans, etc.) on a heritage site. This does not, however, include actual conservation activities for which there is a separate term. "}
{"id": "30384676-4d61-4111-828c-0eeb9fea5b9f", "value": "The act of living, inhabiting or continuing to utilise a certain place"}

{"id": "48672a7b-0e0f-4fea-95fd-410e2394382b", "value": "The act of rebuilding an archaeological site or a place to its known and earlier state that was damaged or destroyed . In this case, the definition includes sites where both the original materials have been used and those in reconstruction where a mixture or additional \"modern\" and new materials and techniques are used. It is distinguished from \"Restoration\" by this use of new materials. "}

{"id": "7216b7e0-1751-41cd-94c4-4e747b79a903", "value": "To upgrade a building, or parts of it, with newer finish materials, furniture, fixtures, or equipment. To only include activities which do not fall under construction e.g. adding electricity, painting, replacing old water pipes."}
{"id": "032a0593-8723-40b1-acdf-f32e8c9ece2e", "value": "A path or route leading from one place to another, often including a built or anthropogenically modified/altered surface "}

{"id": "7812690e-9fc2-465a-98d1-5907d658e4a2", "value": "The act of digging or creating a hole/trench with heavy duty machinery for a purpose other than mining/quarrying. This term can be used to cover archaeological excavation or excavation for the purposes of looting."}
{"id": "b8296f1e-483d-4455-9725-2d6cf1959b76", "value": "The act of turning/breaking up the earth, predominantly in preparation for the planting of crops. "}
{"id": "c49fc850-6d0e-49d9-936e-fe5db295792e", "value": "The installation and use of a centre pivot irrigation system for the provision of water to an area."}

{"id": "61fcf7bb-cd40-428d-b6c6-7722c2cf9a75", "value": "The act of building, including structures, such as housing, infrastructure etc., and the resulting product/s. These activities can be on an industrial/public scale, or at a much smaller 'domestic' scale."}
{"id": "d49b664c-91ba-40d6-8432-6a788c3dfb5c", "value": "The act of clearing and/or flattening/destroying ground or archaeological features/modern buildings etc., using mechanised machinery."}
{"id": "8c799cfa-7b70-440b-aa20-b40f3e59cbf6", "value": "An exothermic process involving the oxidation of material, sending out light and heat and possibly producing smoke."}
{"id": "bb25f011-563e-48f1-ad01-562be938fbcc", "value": "The act of people moving across a heritage site, which can cause damage to the features and erosion."}
{"id": "2aa9f531-e99b-46e8-9e40-1cfba7f2d2b8", "value": "Sudden movement/vibrations of the earth's crust e.g. earthquakes"}

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "3d8e801f-7a60-4492-9ac8-826e85f34bec", "value": "Archaeological field survey incorporates a range of methods leading to the detection, identification and documentation of the material traces of past human activity. Survey collects information about the location, distribution and organisation of past human cultures across a given study area. Excavation is the exposure, processing and recording of archaeological remains. Survey generally proceeds and complements excavation, and is external and horizontal in extent whereas excavation is internal and vertical."}

skos:Concept.skos:definition: {"id": "2dd8ff0c-c175-4b4f-8e65-329472a9f76f", "value": "A general term for the weatherproof coat on the external and internal walls of a building. It is used both as protective and decorative layer."}

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: {"id": "aa085dcf-c304-4484-b10b-6b20b43dedf6", "value": "Air Survey Photographs, UCL Institute of Archaeology Special Collections"}

skos:Concept.skos:definition: {"id": "6eee4267-bace-4fad-80de-8dc88f565029", "value": "Limited"}
{"id": "a935191e-6b24-4737-a377-97c5c0f5acc5", "value": "Negligible"}
{"id": "3eb82d65-b3ef-453f-8bf1-f413731713f3", "value": "Substantial"}
{"id": "d0d0f6b2-b9ad-4574-a61a-e7a40bf60933", "value": "Partial"}
{"id": "65c02e22-a36f-4f57-95d4-3605b0aabfbc", "value": "Possible extent of impact of risk"}
{"id": "015a4c8c-ede6-468c-a47c-354d6e8f208f", "value": "Nearly all or total"}

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "6cb2f18a-f73c-4b23-a3c9-5ffef66829d7", "value": "The risk of damage caused to archaeological sites/features via fire. This can include both risk of damage caused by the flames of the fire, as well as risk of smoke damage."}
{"id": "8f239a20-d94e-4e2e-9242-d8ecd1ff2977", "value": "Natural feature; indicates use of this natural feature"}
{"id": "5ad10174-2250-48a8-be84-90ef896d22ad", "value": "Relating to the use of a site/place for communication and/or artistic purposes (e.g. rock art)."}

{"id": "1b1b8f33-8160-4a41-b924-ef6fa1d34c7e", "value": "Damage causing archaeological sites or features to fall in/subside or to become structurally unsound, or the structural integrity of the site or feature to be compromised. This may include the partial or full demolition/destruction of a site or feature. This category includes structural deformation, inclination and swelling."}

skos:Concept.skos:definition: {"id": "c5454945-5d03-4194-9cd7-3b2b9dc086c9", "value": "Relating to the deliberate destruction or damage to public or private property, without obvious reason."}

{"id": "03f2ea15-53c6-44f5-8e7c-d931fcaafbbd", "value": "Social factors that contribute to deterioration processes of the fabric of heritage sites. Some uses might have a positive impact as they enhance certain values while others might compromise ascribed values and could lead to the deterioration of the heritage site. \"Religious\" is technically part of this, but is distinguished separately in this database."}

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "20320c25-0a51-4c4f-811c-7cc660fc2854", "value": "Relating to the use of a site/place for communication and/or artistic purposes."}
{"id": "1b1064f5-614a-4c71-bb6c-4969ed9187fc", "value": "For use with \"No Visible/Known\""}

skos:Concept.skos:definition: {"id": "4d28cf2e-bf59-42de-a0b3-3f6e6fc4b407", "value": "A cairn of tower-like construction, circular or quadrangular, clearly recognisable by the presence of masonry, that may contain or cover burial(s) or remains interred in a built hollow or feature."}

{"id": "3fbdfe26-bf14-4d49-bc00-1558c7398024", "value": "An enclosure structure composed of three or more clearly distinct spaces (courtyard/cell) in a complex organization. This type of enclosure encompasses \u201ccompound\u201d like organizations, as well as sometimes extended layouts stretching over wide areas (up to 200 m in length). They might reflect more permanent (semi-permanent, sedentary) settlement types. "}

{"id": "24825ecb-18ff-4123-a390-3d433d628c6e", "value": "An enclosure structure composed of two clearly distinct spaces (courtyard/cell) in a consistent structure entity. This type of enclosure is most likely to constitute a temporary pastoral nomadic base camp grouping the dwelling and herding functions in a single structure."}
{"id": "bd020918-1ce3-43d0-bc94-70434c03926c", "value": "A simple structure (of no ostentatious or monumental character) or pit/depression designed to house or mark human (or animal) remains."}

{"id": "bcdb57e1-f7d7-4417-b8c0-cb1de9a133c9", "value": "A tomb/grave/burial surrounded by an outer ring of stones, that may/may not be covered by small stone pile or cairn. There is gap between the tomb/grave/burial and the outer ring (bedrock or ground surface visible)."}
{"id": "2002585c-8f8a-43e9-b7b2-032995856ba1", "value": "Painted object or surface. Specialisation of \"Inscription/Rock Art/Relief\"."}
{"id": "59ba0ad4-62ad-4dec-87fe-d542512bab28", "value": "An object used for games or leisure, only to be used for open air versions (e.g. rock-cut depressions)."}
{"id": "43ba9585-96b9-4098-89d5-c0f1eb282308", "value": "Inscribed object or surface. Specialisation of \"Inscription/Rock Art/Relief\"."}

{"id": "d3e146ef-148b-4213-9b64-4bc25d39408c", "value": "A structure associated with a tomb or cairn of unknown function, suggested by the overall organization of the complex (proximity and/or alignment)."}
{"id": "c4d39f91-e610-4e36-96ca-8e506317ddf1", "value": "A built space within a private area (e.g. of a house or tent) dedicated to the welcoming of visitors."}
{"id": "3982986f-ce54-4dd8-a8ac-3ff00a43c5e7", "value": "A mound of earth and/or stones that may contain burial(s) or remains interred in a built hollow or feature."}

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "b597d9d2-f660-4999-a963-8819abff9ac4", "value": "A structure that allows water to flow under a road or railway."}

skos:Concept.skos:definition: {"id": "b324c5d9-1307-4d01-95e1-f33885f1d2cb", "value": "A complex arrangement of cairns and/or walls which form the shape of a 'gate', i.e. 2 or more long parallel walls/arrangement of cairns, bounded at both ends by a more substantial wall/group of cairns."}

{"id": "c7ffc3d7-08c3-4535-8425-5bcbcd6d8b2b", "value": "A cairn (see feature form definition) hosting a tomb in a natural cavity, covered by a heap of stones or surrounded by a semi-circular stone construction abutted to the outcrop."}

{"id": "9c4845d3-791e-485d-8171-0fc0e65f18aa", "value": "A tower tomb (see definition) surrounded by one or more concentric steps. There is no gap between the central tower and the surrounding steps."}
{"id": "8386ae20-fa4e-45f5-b714-5a24c077f41c", "value": "A wall used to retain soil for agricultural or other purposes."}

{"id": "a7693727-7c52-4835-8665-18b90ca930ef", "value": "Or 'pendant tail'. A linear arrangement or 'tail' made of elongated and linear mounds of stones, masoned structures, stone piles, or a masonry wall with internal compartments (other varieties are possible). "}

{"id": "e6acca24-07e6-4666-b3d7-6e96b17b7ff5", "value": "An enclosure structure composed of a single space (of a courtyard type, mostly unroofed) delimitated by a wall or alignment of stones. This type of enclosure would encompass corrals and pens intended to park domesticated animal herds."}

{"id": "83900e8f-97d7-401f-86d2-235ec675201b", "value": "A cairn of tower-like construction (see feature form definition for tower), clearly recognisable by the presence of masonry, that may contain or cover burial(s) or remains interred in a built hollow or feature, and surrounded by an outer ring of masonry. The space between the inner tower and outer ring is filled with stone and/or sediment at least up to a certain height."}
{"id": "46466252-a1e7-4624-b2bf-1b719f8312e4", "value": "Carved object or surface. Specialisation of \"Inscription/Rock Art/Relief\"."}

{"id": "930678b6-68d9-43d2-8675-98b7fbca3426", "value": "Stairs: A structure or modified rock-surface designed to bridge a vertical distance by dividing it into smaller distances called steps. Step: a flat surface, especially one in a series, on which to place one's foot when moving from one level to another. This term should only be used in the database when describing a separate feature, i.e. rock-cut steps, not a feature inside another feature (i.e. a staircase in a house)."}
{"id": "e3d6d510-eff8-4632-869e-d8dbbb63f7f2", "value": "Unroofed structure (enclosure) designed to keep animals in."}

{"id": "e95594fd-5360-4f99-abf2-c41c4daa1e6d", "value": "A stepped tower tomb (see definition) surrounded by an outer ring of stones. There is a gap between the inner tower and outer ring (bedrock or ground surface visible)."}
{"id": "8cd7164a-75b1-4f21-8eb1-146a4a8e6d98", "value": "A man-made level surface designed to create a level area for a particular purpose, e.g. agriculture."}
{"id": "bdf6e8c2-d047-477f-96b7-657ee775ab5d", "value": "Man-made raised or constructed surface where one end is built higher than its opposite end, creating an even, but sloping platform."}

{"id": "58a91a36-2464-4b03-b017-cd601da77720", "value": "A small concentration of stones with no visible architectural organisation (no masonry or stone alignments) up to 2 m in diameter and 30 cm in height. Anything bigger falls into the \u201cCairn\u201d category."}

{"id": "2edaf7e4-df86-460b-bac6-056313f27bac", "value": "A wall (see definition there) constructed of multiple 'cells', i.e. with openings. In effect, the wall is formed of adjoining structures in a linear arrangement."}

{"id": "06abd567-ccb2-41c5-9825-4045c33bcad7", "value": "A concentration of stones forming a substantial mound, more than 2 m in diameter and 30 cm in height. Anything smaller falls into the \u201cStone pile\u201d category."}
{"id": "60871e3f-59b9-4321-a1d6-1bceef691582", "value": "Man-made raised surface designed to create an even, generally level area for a particular purpose, e.g. the construction of a building. "}

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "38f38de7-8c30-431a-9c70-dc6cceecf827", "value": "An elongated shape with one wider end, curvilinear or rectilinear (rounded or square), that deceases in width along its length until it ends at a point."}

skos:Concept.skos:definition: {"id": "017b96ea-0990-42a3-9589-50183e05c0e4", "value": "The pressing or packing down of archaeological sites/artefacts/soils and so the material becomes flattened and/or compressed."}

{"id": "a330e47d-042a-4115-b7f8-00bb5596959f", "value": "Deposits burying/concealing features of archaeological significance, this can include the effects of sedimentation, rock falls, dumping of non-local material and/or the erection of new buildings or structures. This could be also caused by vegetation/tree cover. It also includes sites that are only partially covered."}

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "11b0e194-5497-4a8e-81ab-019cd145c2a1", "value": "The dispersal/spread of archaeological material/objects across the surface or subsurface of an archaeological site. This is often the result of ploughing."}

{"id": "4790647b-186b-4305-81c5-c6d155950e35", "value": "Changes in the shape/form of landforms or the topography of a site as the result of activities, such as the bulldozing/dumping of non-local material."}

{"id": "cd05d4fc-6ea3-40cb-b7fe-aec1f7df8d75", "value": "The limiting of movement into and around an archaeological site. This can be due to activities such as inundation, as well as occupation/use of the site for military purposes."}

skos:Concept.skos:definition: {"id": "636e6b20-fd81-4061-8d97-839077d41819", "value": "Measurement derived from the analysis of satellite or aerial imagery (e.g. Google Earth, georectified satellite imagery and aerial photography)."}

{"id": "2b8fd14c-746d-430e-8fad-0b3f83104c46", "value": "The process of archaeological material being worn away/weathered, often due to natural causes (exposure to wind, rain, sunlight, as well as salt crystalization, insects and pests damage, and growth of micro-organisms). "}
{"id": "72879a1b-01d0-43c7-ae03-2ad036bc5f56", "value": "The drainage/percolation of harmful chemicals/waste materials into the soils of an archaeological site."}
{"id": "96f82ac5-e7fd-4a82-8860-1cec220c6bfb", "value": "Impact on visual integrity, potential loss of aesthetic value."}
{"id": "1f59487f-9508-4481-a272-4d0addc72f0e", "value": "Powdering of renders and surface finishing."}
{"id": "fbeb4a61-cea6-47e9-90b4-870de68a4f59", "value": "The movement of earth/soil, not necessarily leading to the alteration of landforms and/or the burial of archaeological sites."}
{"id": "7aa1bcb6-f78e-4cd0-b06d-648c89d6b1cf", "value": "The removal of archaeological material from a site, often resulting from activities such as looting or archaeological excavation."}

{"id": "25009f26-475e-408e-9a75-93dc475f55c1", "value": "Damage or alteration to an archaeological site/feature where the result does not cause the feature to become structurally unsound/compromised."}

{"id": "c8a86a1a-51b0-4a19-a640-c232395a9020", "value": "Changes in the shape/form of landforms or the topography of a site as the result of activities, such as the bulldozing/dumping of non-local material."}

{"id": "238355b4-a177-4d09-bdd0-eb4c9fbb1fc1", "value": "The damage caused to archaeological sites/features via fire. This can include both damage caused by the flames of the fire, as well as smoke damage."}

{"id": "452888cd-1a3c-4df9-8a6e-69b2b6c63ece", "value": "The dispersal/spread of archaeological material/objects across the surface or subsurface of an archaeological site. This is often the result of ploughing."}

{"id": "f2aa625f-55be-42b6-abf5-0aa3f5f8d153", "value": "Damage causing archaeological sites or features to fall in/subside or to become structurally unsound, or the structural integrity of the site or feature to be compromised. This may include the partial or full demolition/destruction of a site or feature. This category includes structural deformation, inclination and swelling. "}
{"id": "c17bf07e-e28c-45f5-912b-b313cd2aae64", "value": "Detachment of plaster (renders) or preparatory layer and paint layer or surface finishing."}
{"id": "f2a3accf-319b-4b47-9097-27a291d5c66d", "value": "The effects of water on archaeological features and sites, this includes rising damp, structural decay, rotting, rusting etc."}

{"id": "c3bc4e14-d7a0-49a1-8381-4792e67a1d7d", "value": "The limiting of movement into and around an archaeological site. This can be due to activities such as inundation, as well as occupation/use of the site for military purposes."}

{"id": "624da07f-7764-42c4-a766-666ed8c9ef1d", "value": "The deliberate removal and relocation of archaeological features from one site to another. This may be done to protect archaeological features (e.g. prevent its destruction via inundation etc.) or for other reasons."}

{"id": "54a6b5a7-00bd-4713-bd64-366c7876b425", "value": "To be used when there is no (obvious) damage to the site or feature, but the visual aspect of the heritage is altered. For example with electricity cables running over a wall, or a large shelter built over the site."}

{"id": "2823d463-93e1-4037-b5ba-260cec5c677e", "value": "Deposits burying/concealing features of archaeological significance, this can include the effects of sedimentation, rock falls, dumping of non-local material and/or the erection of new buildings or structures. It also covers sites that are only partially covered."}
{"id": "672cbdef-680a-433e-b232-40785aa88e40", "value": "The pressing or packing down of archaeological sites/artefacts/soils and so the material becomes flattened and/or compressed."}
{"id": "19123978-cd08-4e90-abea-bacccedd18c8", "value": "Unknown"}
{"id": "d95d594c-e0ce-4a09-8988-00559fc7fd30", "value": "The removal of archaeological material from a site, often resulting from activities such as looting or archaeological excavation."}

{"id": "df2db880-503c-48c0-bf82-1e8811bcf01c", "value": "The damage caused to archaeological sites/features via fire. This can include both damage caused by the flames of the fire, as well as smoke damage."}

{"id": "832db9b5-c352-4d8d-98da-41fa9243a9e1", "value": "The dispersal/spread of archaeological material/objects across the surface or subsurface of an archaeological site. This is often the result of ploughing."}
{"id": "9076d6c1-12fa-4a6f-b6ad-e5b5a1ec07d6", "value": "The drainage/percolation of harmful chemicals/waste materials into the soils of an archaeological site."}
{"id": "600899ca-bad7-4949-bb6e-fd4bc80b0da8", "value": "Powdering of renders or surface finishing."}

{"id": "396f154e-fa10-4cb7-99ef-5fe75f733a86", "value": "Damage or alteration to an archaeological site/feature where the result does not cause the feature to become structurally unsound/compromised."}
{"id": "37f94f16-b72b-46f1-bd50-49b27c06d705", "value": "Loss of the upper layer of the feature."}

{"id": "dcde1533-96b8-4c62-8574-3fb3462212c9", "value": "The process of archaeological material being worn away/weathered, often due to natural causes (exposure to wind, rain, sunlight, as well as salt crystalization, insects and pests damage, and growth of micro-organisms)."}

{"id": "d572aba2-bf1c-4bfa-8f67-4db6b50cd0ad", "value": "Changes in the shape/form of landforms or the topography of a site as the result of activities, such as the bulldozing/dumping of non-local material."}

{"id": "933082d7-a681-4be8-adb9-3fab06fda4ff", "value": "The limiting of movement into and around an archaeological site. This can be due to activities such as inundation, as well as occupation/use of the site for military purposes."}

{"id": "f2b1d4da-5020-4877-89eb-fe97a52561e3", "value": "Cracks will occur as a result of stress to structures. Cracks that occur within a limited/small area will not cause structural instability, however from fractures rainwater enters the structure and also plants and vegetation are often starts to grow-out resulting into structural damage and destabilization. Recording and monitoring of cracks is an important step to understand whether they are enlarging or any deformation is in progress."}
{"id": "36cff850-1d02-4ed1-9a1e-2438c219f63a", "value": "Detachment of plaster (render), preparatory layer, paint layer, or surface finishing."}

{"id": "201d76c2-09cd-405b-a7f4-a34c6ce812e3", "value": "The deliberate removal and relocation of archaeological features from one site to another. This may be done to protect archaeological features (e.g. prevent its destruction via inundation etc.) or for other reasons."}
{"id": "ddddb07e-1cb4-4579-b3e1-815035c07c37", "value": "For use with \"No Visible/Known\""}

skos:Concept.skos:definition: {"id": "198b149e-8886-4810-8abc-39d5a8efad79", "value": "Rapid recording and collection of archaeological data carried out before construction and development projects."}

{"id": "3ee77fa7-551d-4e5b-aec3-07464a21822f", "value": "The monitoring of the excavation of a hole made under controlled circumstances. Any archaeological evidence that comes to light is recorded by the archaeologist during the course of the work."}

{"id": "bc2ab3eb-7263-4331-ac16-6a838bcb2d8e", "value": "The taking of photographs during informal site visits, which may be undertaken by amateur archaeologists or architectural students. More formal, detailed surveys should be termed Photographic Survey."}

{"id": "db1eafb2-6230-4af8-b28d-c735e5bd93ab", "value": "Controlled intrusive fieldwork by archaeological specialists which examines, records and interprets archaeological deposits, features and structures and, as appropriate, retrieves artefacts and ecofact remains within a specified area or site on land or within the inter-tidal zone."}
{"id": "562fb4bf-6730-4577-b51e-9fdcfe38814d", "value": "Detailed survey using an unmanned aerial vehicle, such as a drone, to record a heritage place or feature."}

{"id": "79c94d69-8595-4b2e-b032-4c8ff84b4e7f", "value": "Recording and analysis of built structures utilising close observation as well as manual or electronic survey equipment such as GPS and REDM (Reflectorless Electromagnetic Distance Measurement). It includes producing measured drawings on site or building by hand measurement, and/or by using various heritage recording tools to produce plans, elevations, etc."}

{"id": "94acb128-9a8c-4a85-a044-80f5843d40cf", "value": "Archaeological Activity: The non intrusive and intrusive processes by which information is collected about the location, distribution and organisation of past human activities. The approaches can be either extensive or intensive depending the objectives that need to be addressed. Heritage Activity: Programmes of research that seek to identify the archaeological and/or architectural significance of a site or landscape."}
